{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8f24e136-eec3-4739-ab1c-403d8ac5da5d","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited        # enable core dumps\n/usr/libexec/report_crash   # may need SIP adjustment\n```\n\nCore files land in `/cores/` (requires SIP's `kern.coredump` enabled).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6d0c0b6f-1021-4dcb-b7e5-682c48400b13","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":282},"id":"7fcb5504-79e3-4d27-89bd-07a3a72f8fa8","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:59:38.173Z","parentId":"edf7061d-cffa-45db-a68a-fae195123dbb"}
